root_causes: Range/missing check flags missing values as errors even though question is NotRequired (missing should be allowed).
Range check uses miss(v) in the error condition instead of only checking non-missing values.

Other-text (OE) validation is incorrect: it uses STRING(...) and a malformed RTRIM/LTRIM expression (comparison and string trimming are applied in the wrong order), so it will not reliably detect empty OE text for B1cx4_9_other.
instructions: Do not treat missing numeric cells as an error when the question is NotRequired. Replace the range/missing selection condition with a test that only flags out-of-range values for non-missing cells. Example: sel if B1cx4_dochecks = 1 AND NOT miss(v) AND (v < 0 OR v > 999).

Fix the OE presence check to operate on the actual string variable (or convert and compare properly). For example (if B1cx4_9_other is string):
COMPUTE B1cx4_oeerr = 0.
IF (B1cx4_dochecks = 1 AND NOT miss(B1cx4_9) AND B1cx4_9 > 0 AND RTRIM(LTRIM(B1cx4_9_other)) = '') B1cx4_oeerr = 1.
Then select cases where B1cx4_oeerr = 1 to list respid and the OE variable.

If B1cx4_9_other is numeric in your environment, convert it to string first and then trim/compare; but do so correctly (STRING(var,Fw.) produces a string representation of a number — compare that result to '' after trimming).

Keep the AutoSum check as-is but ensure the numeric types and rounding/precision are consistent with the Precision=3 requirement (if decimal places are allowed, consider using a tolerance when comparing sums).

root_causes: Script flags missing values though question is NotRequired (should allow missings)
Missing validation that the sum or comparison matches S7['5'] as per the question's ValidationCode (CompareNum3D...)
No precision check (Precision = 3) — script does not validate decimal precision
Script does not restrict selection to non-missing values before range checks (current sel if uses miss(v) OR v<0 OR v>999)
instructions: Do not flag missing values. Replace the selection line with a condition that only evaluates non-missing responses. Example: sel if ~miss(v) & (v < 0 or v > 999).
Add the numeric-range validation exactly: enforce v >= 0 and v <= 999 (inclusive) as you already partially do, but only for non-missing values.

Implement the required validation that compares the aggregate (or relevant comparison) to f('S7')['5'] per ValidationCode. For example, after checking subitems, compute SUM(A1x5_51 ... A1x5_9) or use the project's CompareNum3D equivalent to ensure the sum equals f('S7')['5'].
Add a precision check to ensure values conform to Precision = 3 (no more than 3 decimal places) if the survey requires it — e.g. flag values where ROUND(v,3) <> v for non-missing v.
Ensure logical gating/entry conditions are respected if any (none listed here), but do not treat NotRequired questions as invalid when missing.

root_causes: Script flags missing values though question is NotRequired (should allow missings)
Does not implement the entry condition isTest() — the question should be validated/displayed only in test mode
No precision enforcement (Precision = 4) or numeric checks are present
instructions: Do not flag missing values. Replace sel if miss(v) with a condition that only evaluates non-missing values (e.g. sel if ~miss(v) & <invalid-condition>), or remove missing-value selection entirely for a NotRequired question.

Apply the entry condition gating: run validation only when isTest() is true. Ensure the script is executed (or the sel if applies) only in test mode (e.g. wrap validation in a check for test-mode or include isTest() in the sel if clause).
Add precision enforcement for 4 decimal places where required — e.g. for non-missing v, flag if ROUND(v,4) <> v.
If any numeric bounds or additional validation rules exist for these items, implement them; otherwise only validate numeric format/precision and respect NotRequired / entry condition.
